Reasoning: The paper describes the hardware design and control architecture of a custom-built quadruped robot, which is used to explore various research problems in legged locomotion using both traditional and learning-based techniques. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of learning-based techniques, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also discusses gait transitions and preliminary results in turning, which suggests that it may belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of computer vision techniques, which suggests that it may also belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
